  "prompt": "Is O-ve universal donor?",
  "response": "No, O negative (O-) is not the universal donor for all types of blood transfusions. While O negative is considered the \"universal donor\" for red blood cells because it can be given to people with any blood type without causing a serious transfusion reaction, it is not universal for all blood components. \n\nFor plasma transfusions, for example, AB positive is the universal donor plasma type. For whole blood or platelet transfusions, other considerations come into play.\n\nO negative blood is critically important because:\n1. It can be given to people with any blood type in emergency situations\n2. It is often used in trauma cases when there's no time to test a patient's blood type\n3. It is always in high demand at hospitals\n\nHowever, it's not completely \"universal\" in all transfusion scenarios.",
